    <h2>FAQ</h2>
    <h3>What number bases are supported?</h3>
    <p>Binary (base 2), Octal (base 8), Decimal (base 10), and Hexadecimal (base 16). The tool converts to all four simultaneously.</p>

    <h3>Is there a size limit?</h3>
    <p>The tool uses BigInt for arbitrary precision, so it handles very large numbers without floating-point rounding errors. Input is limited to 1MB.</p>

    <h3>Is my data safe?</h3>
    <p>Yes. All conversion happens in your browser. No data is sent to any server.</p>

    <h3>Why do programmers use hexadecimal so often?</h3>
    <p>One hex digit represents exactly 4 binary bits (a nibble), so two hex digits represent one byte. This makes hex a compact and readable shorthand for binary data — far easier to scan than a long string of 0s and 1s, and more meaningful than decimal for byte-level work.</p>

    <h3>What do the 0x, 0b, and 0o prefixes mean?</h3>
    <p>These are standard programming prefixes indicating number base: <code>0x</code> for hexadecimal, <code>0b</code> for binary, and <code>0o</code> for octal. This tool strips them automatically so you can paste values from code without editing them first.</p>
